05912nam a22008175i 9780812205176DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979779114  a97808122051767 a10.9783/97808122051762doi  a(DE-B1597)449502  a(OCoLC)794700696  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360202bisacsh1 aWitgen, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aAn Infinity of Nations :bHow the Native New World Shaped Early North America /cMichael Witgen. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (456 p.) :b10 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue. The Long Invisibility of the Native New World -- tPART I. Discovery -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Place and Belonging in Native North America -- tChapter 2. The Rituals of Possession and the Problems of Nation -- tPART II. The New World -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 3. The Rebirth of Native Power and Identity -- tChapter 4. European Interlopers and the Politics of the Native New World -- tPART III. The Illusion of Empire -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 5. An Anishinaabe Warrior’s World -- tChapter 6. The Great Peace and Unraveling Alliances -- tPART IV. Sovereignty. The Making of North America’s New Nations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 7. The Counterfactual History of Indian Assimilation -- tEpilogue. Louis Riel, Native Founding Father -- tGlossary of Native Terms -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn Infinity of Nations explores the formation and development of a Native New World in North America. Until the middle of the nineteenth century, indigenous peoples controlled the vast majority of the continent while European colonies of the Atlantic World were largely confined to the eastern seaboard. To be sure, Native North America experienced far-reaching and radical change following contact with the peoples, things, and ideas that flowed inland following the creation of European colonies on North American soil. Most of the continent's indigenous peoples, however, were not conquered, assimilated, or even socially incorporated into the settlements and political regimes of this Atlantic New World. Instead, Native peoples forged a New World of their own. This history, the evolution of a distinctly Native New World, is a foundational story that remains largely untold in histories of early America.Through imaginative use of both Native language and European documents, historian Michael Witgen recreates the world of the indigenous peoples who ruled the western interior of North America. The Anishinaabe and Dakota peoples of the Great Lakes and Northern Great Plains dominated the politics and political economy of these interconnected regions, which were pivotal to the fur trade and the emergent world economy. Moving between cycles of alliance and competition, and between peace and violence, the Anishinaabeg and Dakota carved out a place for Native peoples in modern North America, ensuring not only that they would survive as independent and distinct Native peoples but also that they would be a part of the new community of nations who made the New World.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHISTORYzUnited StatesxColonial Period (1600-1775). 0aIndians of North AmericaxColonizationxHistory. 0aIndians of North AmericaxColonization. 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relationsxTo 1789. 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relationsyTo 1789. 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericaxSocial life and customs. 4aAmerican